{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}
In [[Dvaita]] [[theology]], '''Nitya-samsarins''', as classified by [[Shri Madhvacharya]], are [[soul]]s which are [[eternity|eternally]] [[reincarnation|transmigrating]].

Madhva divides souls into three classes: one class of souls which qualify for liberation ([[Mukti-yogyas]]), another subject to eternal rebirth or eternal transmigration (Nitya-samsarins), and a third class that is eventually condemned to eternal [[hell]] or [[Andhatamas]] ([[Tamo-yogyas]]).<ref>Tapasyananda, Swami.  ''Bhakti Schools of Vedanta'' pg. 177.</ref>

Nitya-samsarins delight only in [[worldliness|worldly]] [[Value (personal and cultural)|value]]s and feel no need for [[ethics|ethical]] and [[Spirituality|spiritual]] life. By reaping the fruits of their own actions, they pass through continuous [[birth]]s and [[death]]s eternally.

